现存最古老的印度记录有{{link-en|舒爾巴經|Sulba Sutras}}（断代不同，在公元前8世纪到公元2世纪）<ref name="Boyer 1991 loc=China and India p. 207">{{Harv|Boyer|1991|loc="China and India" p. 207}}</ref>，这是一份宗教著作的附录，包括了建设不同形状祭坛的简单规则，例如正方形、长方形、平行四边 形和其它图形<ref>T. K. Puttaswamy, "The Accomplishments of Ancient Indian Mathematicians", pp. 411–2, in {{Cite book|title=Mathematics Across Cultures: The History of Non-western Mathematics|editor1-first=Helaine|editor1-last=Selin|editor1-link=Helaine Selin|editor2-first=Ubiratan|editor2-last=D'Ambrosio|editor2-link=Ubiratan D'Ambrosio|year=2000|publisher=[[Springer_Science+Business_Media|Springer]]|isbn=1-4020-0260-2|ref=harv|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>。和埃及相似，数学最初的祭坛应用指明了数学的起源之一是宗教仪式<ref name="Boyer 1991 loc=China and India p. 207"/>。舒爾巴經还给出了构造和给定正方形面积（大致）相同的圆的方法，这隐含了对pi值不同精度的计算<ref>R. P. Kulkarni, "[http://www.new.dli.ernet.in/rawdataupload/upload/insa/INSA_1/20005af9_32.pdf The Value of π known to Śulbasūtras] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206150545/http://www.new.dli.ernet.in/rawdataupload/upload/insa/INSA_1/20005af9_32.pdf |date=2012-02-06 }}", ''Indian Journal for the History of Science'', 13 '''1''' (1978): 32-41</ref><ref>J.J. Connor, E.F. Robertson. ''The Indian Sulba Sutras'' Univ. of St. Andrew, Scotland [http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/HistTopics/Indian_sulbasutras.html] {{Wayback|url=http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/HistTopics/Indian_sulbasutras.html |date=20160407212457 }} The values for π are 4 x (13/15)<sup>2</sup> (3.0044...), 25/8 (3.125), 900/289 (3.11418685...), 1156/361 (3.202216...), and 339/108 (3.1389).</ref>。除此之外，他们还将2的平方根计算到了小数点后7位，列出了勾股数，并且说明了勾股定理<ref>J.J. Connor, E.F. Robertson. ''The Indian Sulba Sutras'' Univ. of St. Andrew, Scotland [http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/HistTopics/Indian_sulbasutras.html] {{Wayback|url=http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/HistTopics/Indian_sulbasutras.html |date=20160407212457 }}</ref>。而这一切成果都曾在古巴比伦数学中出现，表明了美索不达米亚文明的影响<ref name="Boyer 1991 loc=China and India p. 207"/>。然而，目前还不清楚舒爾巴經是否影响了日后的印度数学。和中国一样，印度数学同样缺乏连续性，重大的突破往往伴随着长时间的死寂<ref name="Boyer 1991 loc=China and India p. 207"/>。

